<h2 id="pros">What HVAC Contractors Love About Jobber</h2>

<div class="prose max-w-none">
<h3>1. Intuitive Scheduling Interface</h3>
<p>74% of users praise Jobber's drag-and-drop scheduling. The calendar view makes it easy to see technician availability, reschedule jobs, and avoid double-bookings. Color-coding by job type helps dispatchers quickly identify emergency calls versus routine maintenance.</p>

<p>One contractor in Phoenix told us: "We went from 3-4 scheduling mistakes per week to maybe one per month. The visual calendar just makes sense."</p>

<h3>2. Strong Customer Communication</h3>
<p>Automated text and email notifications keep customers informed. 81% of HVAC contractors report fewer "where is my technician?" calls after implementing Jobber's communication features.</p>

<p>Key communication features:</p>
<ul>
<li>Appointment confirmations and reminders</li>
<li>Technician en-route notifications with GPS tracking</li>
<li>Job completion photos sent automatically</li>
<li>Follow-up review requests</li>
</ul>

<h3>3. Mobile App Functionality</h3>
<p>Technicians can access job details, capture photos, create invoices, and collect payments from their phones. The offline mode works reasonably well, though not as robust as some competitors.</p>

<p>67% of field technicians rate the mobile app as "easy to use," though speed and reliability issues persist in areas with poor cell coverage.</p>

<h3>4. QuickBooks Integration</h3>
<p>Jobber syncs well with QuickBooks Online and Desktop. Financial data flows cleanly, reducing double-entry and bookkeeping errors. This is crucial for HVAC contractors who need accurate job costing and profit tracking.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="cons">Jobber's Biggest Weaknesses</h2>

<div class="prose max-w-none">
<h3>1. Limited Equipment Tracking</h3>
<p>This is Jobber's biggest weakness for HVAC contractors. You can't track equipment serial numbers, warranty information, or maintenance history effectively. There's no equipment lifecycle management or automated maintenance scheduling based on equipment age.</p>

<p>A commercial HVAC contractor in Denver explained: "We have 200+ units under service contracts. Jobber just can't handle the equipment tracking we need. We ended up keeping a separate spreadsheet."</p>

<h3>2. Weak Inventory Management</h3>
<p>Jobber's inventory features are basic. You can track parts on hand and set reorder points, but there's no truck stock management, automatic inventory adjustments, or integration with parts suppliers. 43% of HVAC users cite inventory management as a major pain point.</p>

<h3>3. Basic Reporting</h3>
<p>Reports cover the basics (revenue, technician performance, outstanding invoices) but lack depth. You can't easily analyze profit margins by job type, track equipment-specific revenue, or create custom KPI dashboards.</p>

<p>Compared to <a href="/hvac/crm/servicetitan-vs-housecall-pro">ServiceTitan's advanced analytics</a>, Jobber's reporting feels elementary for data-driven HVAC companies.</p>

<h3>4. Payment Processing Costs</h3>
<p>At 2.9% + $0.30 per transaction, Jobber's payment fees are higher than many alternatives. For an HVAC company processing $50,000/month in credit card payments, that's $1,465/month in fees compared to $1,225/month with Square (2.6% + $0.10).</p>

<h3>5. Limited Customization</h3>
<p>You can't modify invoice templates extensively or create complex custom fields. HVAC companies with specific compliance requirements or unique workflows often find Jobber too rigid.</p>
</div>

